	<p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><i><b>Sons and Lovers</b></i> is a British <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1960_in_film" title="1960 in film">1960 film</a> adaptation of the <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D._H._Lawrence" title="D. H. Lawrence">D. H. Lawrence</a> novel <i><a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sons_and_Lovers" title="Sons and Lovers">Sons and Lovers</a></i>. It was adapted by <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T._E._B._Clarke" title="T. E. B. Clarke">T. E. B. Clarke</a> and <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gavin_Lambert" title="Gavin Lambert">Gavin Lambert</a> and directed by <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Cardiff" title="Jack Cardiff">Jack Cardiff</a>. It stars <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trevor_Howard" title="Trevor Howard">Trevor Howard</a>, <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dean_Stockwell" title="Dean Stockwell">Dean Stockwell</a>, <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wendy_Hiller" title="Wendy Hiller">Wendy Hiller</a>, <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_Ure" title="Mary Ure">Mary Ure</a>, <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Lucas_(British_actor)" title="William Lucas (British actor)">William Lucas</a> and <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Pleasence" title="Donald Pleasence">Donald Pleasence</a>.</p>
	<p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">The film won an <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Cinematography" title="Academy Award for Best Cinematography">Academy Award for Best Cinematography</a> <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freddie_Francis" title="Freddie Francis">Freddie Francis</a> and was nominated for <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Actor" title="Academy Award for Best Actor">Best Actor in a Leading Role</a> (Trevor Howard), <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Supporting_Actress" title="Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress">Best Actress in a Supporting Role</a> (Mary Ure), <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Art_Direction" title="Academy Award for Best Art Direction">Best Art Direction-Set Decoration, Black-and-White</a> (<a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_N._Morahan" title="Thomas N. Morahan">Thomas N. Morahan</a>, <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lionel_Couch" title="Lionel Couch">Lionel Couch</a>), <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Directing" title="Academy Award for Directing">Best Director</a>, <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Picture" title="Academy Award for Best Picture">Best Picture</a> and <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Writing_Adapted_Screenplay" title="Academy Award for Writing Adapted Screenplay">Best Writing, Screenplay Based on Material from Another Medium</a>. </p>
	<p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">The film was also entered into the <a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1960_Cannes_Film_Festival" title="1960 Cannes Film Festival">1960 Cannes Film Festival</a>. </p>
